07701nam a22010935i 9783110677522DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019955782  a97831106775227 a10.1515/97831106775222doi  a(DE-B1597)536548  a(OCoLC)1149417777  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aPA1050.3b.P67 2020. 4aPA1050.3b.P67 2020 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a487/.322300aPostclassical Greek :bContemporary Approaches to Philology and Linguistics /ced. by Ilja A. Seržant, Dariya Rafiyenko. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (VIII, 339 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Linguistics. Studies and Monographs [TiLSM] ;v33500tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tContents -- tPostclassical Greek. An Overview -- tSection I: Grammatical Categories -- tPurpose and Result Clauses: ἵνα-hína and ὥστε-hōʹste in the Greek Documentary Papyri of the Roman Period -- tSyntactic Factors in the Greek Genitive- Dative Syncretism: The Contribution of New Testament Greek -- tFuture Periphrases in John Malalas -- tCombining Linguistics, Paleography and Papyrology: The Use of the Prepositions eis, prós and epí in Greek Papyri -- tFuture Forms inPostclassical Greek. Some Remarks on the Septuagint and the New Testament -- tGreek Infinitive-Retreat versus Grammaticalization: An Assessment -- tPostclassical Greek and Treebanks for a Diachronic Analysis -- tSection II: Sociolinguistic Aspects and Variation -- tThe Perfect Paradigm in Theodosius’ Κανόνες: Diathetically Indifferent and Diathetically Non-Indifferent Forms -- tForms of the Directive Speech Act: Evidence from Early Ptolemaic Papyri -- tWhat’s in a (personal) Name? Morphology and Identity in Jewish Greek Literature in the Hellenistic and Roman Periods -- tConfusion of Mood or Phoneme? The Impact of L1 Phonology on Verb Semantics -- tChange in Grammatical and Lexical Structures inPostclassical Greek: Local Dialects and Supradialectal Tendencies -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe language of Postclassical Greek is a somewhat neglected area of research despite the language of this period being well attested with a large number of different sorts of texts ranging from papyri and dialect inscriptions to literary texts by Hellenistic, Roman and Byzantine writers. These texts offer an extensive amount of data and are rather understudied in comparison with texts of the Classical period. This volume aims to fill some of this void by offering an interdisciplinary approach to the language of the period. As such, it brings together contributions from disciplines including usage-based linguistics, theoretical syntax, historical linguistics, papyrologyand palaeography, sociolinguistics and research on multilingualism. It is hoped, therefore, that the volume will appeal to a wide audience interested in exploring language development from several perspectives.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aGreek language, Medieval and late. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aGrammar of Postclassical Greek.  aLanguage Change.  aLanguage Contact.1 aBartolo, Giuseppina di, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBenedetti, Marina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBruno, Carla, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrellin, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDahlgren, Sonja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGianollo, Chiara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaug, Dag Trygve Truslew, 